  "prompt": "What are the best things to do in San Francisco?",
  "response": "San Francisco is a city overflowing with amazing things to see and do! Here's a breakdown of some of the best, organized by category, to help you plan your trip:\n\n**Iconic Landmarks & Must-Sees:**\n\n*   **Golden Gate Bridge:** Walk, bike, or drive across this iconic bridge for breathtaking views. Consider visiting Fort Point for an even closer perspective.  (Walk or bike from the city side, or drive to Vista Point on the Marin side.)\n*   **Alcatraz Island:** Take a ferry to this infamous former prison. Book your tickets *well* in advance (weeks or even months) as they sell out quickly. The audio tour is highly recommended.\n*   **Fisherman's Wharf:** A touristy but fun area. See the sea lions at Pier 39, enjoy fresh seafood, and browse the shops. Don't expect the most authentic SF experience, but it's worth a visit.\n*   **Lombard Street (The \"Most Crooked Street\"):** Drive down this famously winding street (be prepared for slow traffic!) or walk along the sidewalks to take pictures.\n*   **Painted Ladies:** These Victorian houses, made famous by the TV show \"Full House,\" are a classic San Francisco photo op. Alamo Square Park offers a great vantage point.\n*   **Cable Cars:** Ride a cable car up the steep hills for a unique San Francisco experience. Be prepared for lines, especially during peak season. Consider buying a Muni Passport for unlimited rides.\n*   **Golden Gate Park:** A huge urban oasis, even larger than Central Park. Rent a bike, visit the Japanese Tea Garden, de Young Museum, California Academy of Sciences, or the Conservatory of Flowers.\n*   **Chinatown:** One of the oldest and largest Chinatowns in the US. Explore the bustling streets, sample authentic cuisine, and visit the temples.\n\n**Museums & Culture:**\n\n*   **de Young Museum:** Fine art museum in Golden Gate Park, featuring American art from the 17th through 21st centuries, international textile arts and costumes, and art from Africa, Oceania, and the Americas.\n*   **California Academy of Sciences:** A natural history museum, aquarium, planetarium, and rainforest all under one roof in Golden Gate Park. Great for families.\n*   **SFMOMA (San Francisco Museum of Modern Art):** A world-class modern and contemporary art museum.\n*   **Asian Art Museum:** One of the largest museums in the Western world devoted exclusively to Asian art.\n*   **Walt Disney Family Museum:** Located in the Presidio, this museum tells the story of Walt Disney's life and legacy.\n*   **Exploratorium:** An interactive science museum on Pier 15, perfect for kids and adults alike.\n*   **Legion of Honor:** Fine arts museum with a focus on European art, featuring works by Monet, Rodin, and more.  Offers stunning views of the Golden Gate Bridge.\n\n**Neighborhoods to Explore:**\n\n*   **North Beach:** The historic Italian neighborhood, known for its cafes, bookstores (like City Lights), and nightlife.\n*   **Haight-Ashbury:** The birthplace of the hippie counterculture. Explore the vintage shops, record stores, and unique boutiques.\n*   **Mission District:** A vibrant neighborhood with a strong Latin American influence. Enjoy delicious tacos, murals, and a lively atmosphere.\n*   **Castro:** A historically LGBTQ+ neighborhood with a welcoming and inclusive atmosphere.\n*   **Sausalito:** A charming waterfront town across the Golden Gate Bridge. Take a ferry for stunning views of the city skyline.\n\n**Food & Drink:**\n\n*   **Seafood:** Try clam chowder in a sourdough bread bowl, fresh oysters, or Dungeness crab.\n*   **Burritos:** The Mission District is famous for its massive and delicious burritos.\n*   **Dim Sum:** Chinatown offers a wide variety of dim sum restaurants.\n*   **Craft Beer:** San Francisco has a thriving craft beer scene. Visit local breweries and taprooms.\n*   **Coffee:** San Francisco is known for its excellent coffee shops and independent roasters.\n*   **Wine Country:** Take a day trip to Napa or Sonoma to visit wineries and sample California wines.\n\n**Outdoor Activities & Views:**\n\n*   **Hike Lands End:** Enjoy stunning coastal views and explore the ruins of the Sutro Baths.\n*   **Bike the Golden Gate Bridge:** A classic San Francisco experience. Rent a bike near Fisherman's Wharf and ride across the bridge to Sausalito.\n*   **Visit a Park:** Golden Gate Park, Dolores Park, Alamo Square Park, and the Presidio are all great options for relaxing and enjoying the outdoors.\n*   **Angel Island:** Take a ferry to Angel Island for hiking, biking, and stunning views of the Bay Area.\n*   **Baker Beach:** Great views of the Golden Gate Bridge, especially at sunset. Be aware that the northern part of the beach is clothing-optional.\n\n**Things to Consider When Planning:**\n\n*   **Weather:** San Francisco weather can be unpredictable. Layers are always a good idea. Even in summer, fog can roll in and make it feel chilly.\n*   **Transportation:** Public transportation is available, but can be slow. Consider using ride-sharing services, renting a car (parking can be challenging), or walking/biking.  A Muni Passport can be a good deal if you plan to use public transit extensively.\n*   **Cost:** San Francisco is an expensive city. Be prepared to spend more on accommodations, food, and activities.\n*   **Time of Year:** Spring and fall generally offer the best weather. Summer can be foggy and crowded.\n*   **Safety:** Be aware of your surroundings, especially in touristy areas. Don't leave valuables unattended.\n\nTo give you even better recommendations, tell me:\n\n*   **What are your interests (art, history, food, outdoors, nightlife, etc.)?**\n*   **How much time do you have in San Francisco?**\n*   **What's your budget?**\n*   **Who are you traveling with (family, friends, solo, couple)?**\n\nKnowing these details will help me tailor my suggestions to your specific needs and preferences!\n",
